The Two Hour Move Speed Chart
shows the maximum distance the
party can move in two hours. After
determining max speed, roll a nav
check and subtract your penalty from
The Navigation Skill chart. Please
note that characters with the Guide
Perk treat bogs, mountains, and
forests as paths for the sake of max
movement speed. Unless you
critically fail, you cannot move slower
than 2 miles on road or path, and 1
mile in bogs, forests, or mountains.
Each character in the party must test their
stamina every two hours of travel. Each
Time they fail, they will gain an extra level
of exhaustion for the rest of the day. You
can read more about exhaustion in the
Master Rulebook. Characters that have level
three of exhaustion cannot willingly travel
any further, though they can be force
marched by a leader. This risks causing
illness or even death and should only be
done as a last resort.

Last Watch:
The party will have 10 chances to spot the enemies approaching if it is in a field, path, peak, desert, or road.
They will have five chances to see them If it is in a wooded area (forest, mountain, bog, etc).
Sleeping with Equipment
For each point of load that you sleep with, you have a 10% chance of not recovering stamina while resting in a
camp. Ie. If you have a load of 3 while sleeping, you have a 30% chance of not recovering stamina.
Warm Camp
While sleeping at a warm camp, you will recover one tier of stamina that has been lost thru
traveling.
The Camping Minigame is usually played by the naturalist in the group (Stalker, Ranger, Etc) and is used to help
the party recover and help them avoid random encounters.
No Shelter:
You will wake up in the following morning with the Weary
stamina condition. If there is perciptiation, you will wake up
exhausted instead.

If the party must camp in the wilderness at night, it will be up to the party naturalist to find an appropriate
shelter to spend the night. Searching for shelter takes 30 minutes. A tracking check is rolled. If the party has a
enough tents for everyone, then the party will always at least find a level 2 Shelter.
When you are camping in the wilderness, you will want to set up a watch in case of a random attack against your
camp. There are three watch shifts through the night, and characters must sleep for at least two off them or
they will increase their exhaustion level by one. If they do not sleep at all, then they will will at least be
exhausted on the following day if not worse.
If the first encounter pops then roll a D3. On one or two then it falls on the First Watch, on 3 it falls on the mid watch.
If the second encounter pops then roll a D3. On one then it falls on the mid Watch, on 2 or 3 it falls on the last watch.
If the shelter was warm, then the last watch will have recovered stamina when their shift begins.
Dry Shelter:
A dry camp will negate the penalties for perciptiation (if there is
any). You can turn a dry camp into a warm camp by making a
fire, but this will give you disadvantages against random
encounters.
Safe Camp
A safe camp will give the party a terrain advantage if there is a random encounter at their
hidden camp.
Setting up Watch
Random Encounter
It is up to the watch to spot any enemies approaching the camp and wake up the rest of the fighters before the
enemy arrives. How much time the watch will have to do this depends on how good of a job the watch does.

Camp Ambush
Playing Camp Ambush
The camp ambush will take either 10 rounds or 5 rounds
depending on if you are in a forested area or not. Write the
DD in the DD collumn. The watchmen will get a perception
check each round of the attack. If the watchmen fail the
check, then the enemy moves closer. Once the watchmen
see the enemy, they can alert the camp immediately or
make an acting check DD16 to alert the camp without
letting the enemy know. If this acting check is successful,
then you get the remaining amount of rounds to prepare.

Crew Stamina and Sailing Checks
Whenever you make a sailing check, you must also make a stamina check for your crew. You will make a
stamina check using the chart below and if you fail it, your entire crew will be tired for the rest of the day. If you
fail it by four or more, then they will be weary, and if you fail it by eight or more, they will be exhausted. A
Boatswain may take this check in your stead.
Sailing Speed
If you fail a sailing check, then in the course of your travel today, your vessel will sustain some damage. The
damage sustained will cost 5% of the vessel cost to fix. This will affect the speed that your vessel moves, as well
as the difficulty of future vessel checks. If your vessel receives damage, the game master will randomize when in
your trip the damage occurs and you will make an immediate second sailing check. If you succeed the second
sailing check, you may move on with your damaged vessel. If you fail it, then you will become shipwrecked.
When you are sailing a ship, the captain will choose the amount of hours to sail today and roll a Sailing Check. If
they succeed, then the ship will sail the distance indicated on the Vessel Sheet.

While in a horse chase, you will have a score which represents how far away from your enemy you are. Each point represents 80 feet. The
amount of points to fully escape from any enemy is dependent on the environment. If the difference between your score and the enemy's
score is zero, then melee attacks become possible. At low scores missile attacks become possible as well.
Each round, roll a riding check DD12. On Success, gain three points. On a 20 or higher, gain four instead.
On 25 or higher, gain five instead. If the different between the pursuer's and escapee's score becomes
greater than the amount of points required in the escape chart to the right, then the escapee escapes.
Each round, a random event will occur that can affect the Chase.

one minute. If not, you may try again If two eights are rolled, then the healing occurs in 30
seconds instead of a minute. If three or more eights are rolled, then the healing takes place in
only twelve seconds. You may attempt to heal faster. Give yourself a -X penalty to your check
and you may roll X additional dice when making your heal complete checks.

Restoration
A healing can be used for one of five purposes:
Restoration, Cauterization, Treat Poison, Treat
disease, revive drowned.
Restoration: Recovers Hit points.
Cauterization: Stops Bleeding.
Treat Poison/Disease: Reduces the duration of
Poison or Disease.
Revive Drowned: Prevent a drowned individual from
dying.
Bone Bind: Start a bone healing. Takes 1 month.
A healer can attempt to perform restoration
to an individual once each day, and may
attempt to cauterize a single source of
bleeding once each day. Another healer
cannot attempt to heal the same individual or
wound unless they have a bonus at least 2
points higher than the original healer. If a
superior healer attempts to restore a victim
already restored by another healer, they will
only add HP over and above the amount
added by the original healer. Each instance of
bleeding must be treated separately.

Poison and Disease
Poison Save
If you are exposed to poison or disease, you must take a poison or
disease check. Roll your poison or disease check against the DD of the
contaminant. If you fail, you will suffer the penalty to all your checks
equal to the result on the chart to the left. Additionall, you will suffer a
penalty to your CON. After the effects of the poison or disease wear
off, you will slowly recover CON at a rate of one CON per week. The
duration of the effects will be rolled on the duration chart below. The
penalties will not take effect until the time indicated on the delay chart
are met.
Poison and Disease
Duration
Treating a poison or disease does not outright cure the victim, but
shortens the duration. That means that fatal effects will still cause
death even if treated. Losses of Constitution can often cause death,
especially for older aged victims.
If you are performing a healing check against Poison within 20
minutes of receiving the poison, then you may try to reduce the
severity of the poison with a check.

Mechanics Sheet
Trap Making
There are essentially four kinds of traps that you can make. As soon as you have Mechanics trained or
class role, you can attempt to make all the different kinds of traps that are available. Each type of trap
can be set with various conditions that may require higher level training in order to make them.
Assistance
You may have assistants that help you make a trap faster or better. Your mechanics skill can be boosted
by one by someone that has at least half your level of mechanics. Also, you may be helped by someone
that has alchemy, Trickery, or Tracking Trained to make better traps.
Trap Stealth
Building traps requires a
"Travel Type" Stamina
check every two hours
of work. See Navigation
for more info.

A snare trap is a trap that is meant to immobilize a victim when they trigger the trap. Victims test
acrobatics against your mechanics score +10 and consults the chart below.

Traps for Game and other animals
You may design a trade to catch wild game. If build by a person which has tracking trained, you may
return to this trap to check it. Roll a D10, on a 10, the desired animal will have come into contact with the
trap. Make a tracking check with a -2 penalty. If you succeed against the animal difficulty, then the animal
will be trapped. On a result of one, an animal other than the desired one interacts with the trap.
Lock Picking
You may attempt to pick locks using your mechanics skill. Test your mechanics skill against the lock in
question. You must spend the amount of time described below to attempt to pick the lock. When the
time is elapsed, then make a check.

Trickery Sheet
"Magic" Tricks
Magic tricks which are done by slight of hand can be performed against other humans. To successfully
trick the victim, you must pass a trickery check DD 8+the perception of the victim. This is to do thinks
like make a small object disappear and reappear, etc.
Thievery!
You may use your trickery skill to swipe things from off of the body of a person.

Moderate or higher breeze
Making attacks while swimming is difficult. You will receive a -6 penalty to your attacks while you are
swimming, or submerged in water entirely.
Diving
Minus one for each attack you plan on making
Total
If you fail your check, you will be unable to act this turn. If you fail eight consecutive checks in a two minute
period, you be "Drowned." You can be saved after having drowned by a healer, but it gets more difficult each
round that you have been drowned.
Swimming in freezing water will cause a loss of four stamina per turn. This stamina can only be recovered if
you are exposed to warmth, and only recovers at the normal stamina recovery rate.
Each round that you spend holding your breath you will lose two stamina. If you have the Aquatic talent, then
you only lose 1 stamina per round. If you have the Merman Talent, then you only lose one stamina every
other round. Stamina lost in this way recovers at a rate of 10 stamina per round once you are breathing
normally again.

Stamina
Making a swim check automatically uses a stamina each round unless you have swimming trained or class
role. If you have swimming trained, it will consume a stamina every minute. If it is class roll, it will cause an
increase in daily fatigue every hour that you spend swimming.

Along a Road
When conducting a foraging check, spend two hours and roll a foraging
check. Consult the chart corresponding to your results and roll a D10 to
see what you find. Checks below 14 are unfruitful. If you want to find a
specific item you must roll three higher than the first chart in which the
desired item appears. If you fail, find an item as described above. The
first appearances have been bolded.

Foraging while Traveling
Foraging takes 2 hours to complete. You can forage while traveling by traveling at a "Tracking Speed" If you
Track and Forage at the same time, you will move at Stealthy tracking speed. If you stealth, Track, and Forage
all at once, then move at stealthy tracking speed with an additional -1.
